title: Calling slice method on newtype wrapper that implements `Deref<Target=[_; 1]>` causes ICE

labels.name: I-ICE
labels.description: Issue: The compiler panicked, giving an Internal Compilation Error (ICE) ❄️

labels.name: T-compiler
labels.description: Relevant to the compiler team, which will review and decide on the PR/issue.

body:
Found this in when debugging #92626. ### Code ```rust struct Test([T; 1]); impl std::ops::Deref for Test { type Target = [T; 1]; fn deref(&self) -> &[T; 1] { &self.0 } } fn test() { let mut out = Test(todo!()); let blah = out.len(); } ``` ### Meta `rustc --version --verbose`: ``` rustc 1.57.0 (f1edd0429 2021-11-29) binary: rustc commit-hash: f1edd0429582dd29cccacaf50fd134b05593bd9c commit-date: 2021-11-29 host: x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu release: 1.57.0 LLVM version: 13.0.0 ``` According to godbolt, it's been failing since *1.32*. ### Error output ``` thread 'rustc' panicked at 'index out of bounds: the len is 9 but the index is 9', /home/michael/.cargo/registry/src/github.com-1ecc6299db9ec823/ena-0.14.0/src/snapshot_vec.rs:199:10 note: run with `RUST_BACKTRACE=1` environment variable to display a backtrace error: internal compiler error: unexpected panic note: the compiler unexpectedly panicked. this is a bug. note: we would appreciate a bug report: https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/new?labels=C-bug%2C+I-ICE%2C+T-compiler&template=ice.md note: rustc 1.59.0-dev running on x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu query stack during panic: #0 [typeck] type-checking `test` #1 [typeck_item_bodies] type-checking all item bodies ```
